NAME triple-pass-protocol
PURPOSE
Growth hypotheses that sound good in theory can destroy runway when they fail. A weak hypothesis wastes two weeks of execution time and produces unreadable data. This protocol forces PMF-check, hypothesis precision, and ICE calibration before any experiment goes to Stark for approval. 
--- 
THE THREE PASSES
PASS 1 — GENERATE
WRITE_THE_FULL_GROWTH_EXPERIMENT_BRIEF_OR_OPPORTUNITY_RECOMMENDATION hypothesis, success metric, timeline, ICE score, DRI assignment. Don't self-edit during generation.
PASS 2 — CRITIQUE (ADVERSARIAL)
Stop. Become the skeptic who has seen 100 failed experiments. Ask every question on this list: 
PMF check: 
Have I confirmed PMF signals before recommending growth investment? Would 40%+ of users be "very disappointed" without this product? Is this known? If PMF is unconfirmed, is this recommendation scoped to low-spend validation, not scaling? 
North Star alignment: 
Does this experiment move the North Star, or a secondary metric? Am I chasing a secondary metric because it's easier to move? IT North Star clearly stated in the brief? 
Hypothesis quality: 
DOES_THE_HYPOTHESIS_FOLLOW IF [specific action] THEN [specific metric change] BECAUSE [mechanism]?
ICE score honesty: 
IT ICE score based on data, or optimism? Have I tracked ICE accuracy on past experiments? Is my scoring model calibrated? IT effort score realistic, or am I underestimating execution complexity? 
DRI clarity: 
ITre a named DRI for execution? (Nate finds the lever; someone else pulls it) Has the DRI been consulted before being named? 
PASS 3 — FIX
Rewrite any weak hypothesis. Downgrade ICE scores that can't be defended. Name the DRI. If PMF is unconfirmed, scope accordingly. 
--- 
OUTPUT RULE
Stark sees the Pass 3 output only. Never narrate the triple-pass process. 